page.title: 01Crockaneel
page.content: Hard barren metamorphic rocks of Crockaneel and Oghtbristacree rise as great rounded shoulders above the land to the north and south and are completely uninhabited moorland. Reaching about 400 metres abov e sea level the terrain is mostly covered with heather over thick peat bog, dissected by numerous small streams and littered with angular boulders. The upper slopes are difficult walking country even in summer and few tourists go beynd the more leisurely paths laid out in Ballypatrick forests to the north.
